{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "To manage this system, we employ the well-established model predictive control (MPC) approach.",
    "As MPC is designed under the certainty equivalence principle (CEP) [25], the performance strongly depends on the accuracy of the underlying model; therefore, selecting an appropriate model is crucial to ensure high control performance.",
    "For the systems under consideration in this paper, where vast amounts of data across multiple and heterogeneous operating regions are available, it is often more effective to use an ensemble of data-based models for prediction, rather than relying solely on a single physics-based or black-box model [7].",
    "Let us denote these models, indexed with i ∈ N = {1,..., n}, as M [1],..., M [n], each trained independently on a specific dataset D [1],..., D [n] corresponding to a different operational domain.",
    "The i-th dataset is defined asD [i] = u [i]⊤ y [i]⊤ p ⊤,whereu [i] = u(k) k∈I [i] and y [i] p = y p (k) k∈I [i]are the input-output data collected at time indices within the set I [i]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "As MPC is designed under the certainty equivalence principle (CEP) [25], the performance strongly depends on the accuracy of the underlying model; therefore, selecting an appropriate model is crucial to ensure high control performance.",
    "For the systems under consideration in this paper, where vast amounts of data across multiple and heterogeneous operating regions are available, it is often more effective to use an ensemble of data-based models for prediction, rather than relying solely on a single physics-based or black-box model [7].",
